PART 2: THE DEEP LIFT (8 Phases of Hell)
They hit the button. The platform launches up into the 500-foot enclosed shaft. They are trapped on a 50-foot bronze disc. You need 8 Safe Passages per Phase. 8 Phases total.
Phase 1: The Drop. Hatches above them blow open. Spider Sentinels drop directly onto the platform, weapons hot. (Melee combat, 45 Physical).
Phase 2: The Vents. The lift passes the exhaust vents. Spiders in the walls fire a crossfire of Static Shock into the enclosed space. (Ranged magic, 30 Shock + FP Drain).
Phase 3: The Breach. Spiders climbing the lift chains punch through the floor grating beneath their boots. Sections of the floor become hazardous. (Agility/Might to avoid being pinned).
Phase 4: The Boarders. The spiders from Phase 3 fully breach the surface. The 50-foot disc is now shared with a dozen hostile machines.
Phase 5: The Steam Vents. The lift passes ruptured thermal pipes. Scalding, high-pressure steam floods the shaft, blinding everyone and dealing environmental damage. (Magic/Guile to navigate/shield).
Phase 6: The Rain of Bronze. Hundreds of tiny, newly manufactured spider-drones are dumped down the shaft from the city level. It’s like hail made of sparking metal.
Phase 7: Structural Failure. The sheer weight of the boarders and the damage to the lift causes the platform to violently tilt 30 degrees. (Agility/Might to not slide off the edge into the 300-foot drop).
Phase 8: The Slam. The lift hits the city-level docking bay without decelerating properly. A massive kinetic shockwave. (Brace for impact - 35 Bludgeoning + Stagger).

PART 3: THE DEAD CITY (The Swarm)
They step off the lift. The city they explored hours ago is now a knee-deep, flowing river of 11,000 repurposed Spider Workers. They must run 400 meters through the rooms they know.
Zone 1: The Transit Hub
The Threat: The initial shock of the swarm. They must form a wedge and break into the metal river.
The Action: If they fail here, they are pulled under immediately (30 Shock + Slowed).
Zone 2: The Dining Hall
The Threat: The swarm is pouring over the stone tables and brass plates. The terrain is uneven.
The Action: They can use the tables to stay out of the deepest parts of the swarm, leaping from stone to stone, or bash through the bottlenecks between tables.
Zone 3: The Living Quarters Corridors
The Threat: Spiders are pouring out of every single open bedroom door, hitting them from the flanks as they run.
The Action: They have to protect the flanks. Whoever is on the outside of the formation has to deflect horizontal waves of machines.
Zone 4: The Fabrication Workshops
The Threat: The swarm is weaponizing the environment, knocking over heavy tools and triggering dormant machinery to block the party's path.
Zone 5: The Final Stretch (The 100m Sprint)
The Threat: The Surface Lift is in sight. The swarm knows they are escaping and surges, creating a tidal wave of bronze behind them. Pure, desperate endurance.

PART 4: THE SURFACE LIFT
They reach the final transit hub. The lift is waiting, but the tubes must be played.
Phase 1: The Hold
The Threat: The Swarm crashes into the room.
The Action: The Activator (Orion/Whoever) must play the tubes (W-N-S-E). The rest of the party must generate the 8 Safe Passages to hold the 15-foot chokepoint. If a defender fails, they take 45 Physical Damage as the swarm crushes into them. If the swarm hits the Activator, the launch sequence is interrupted.
Phase 2: The Launch & Escape
The Threat: The lift rockets upward with explosive acceleration. The swarm makes one final, desperate lunge, with hundreds of spiders leaping onto the ascending platform before it clears the shaft.
The Action: The platform is rocketing to the surface. The party must clear the boarders while fighting the G-force of the emergency ascent.
The End: The bronze doors above slam open. They are thrown onto the freezing snow of the Pale. The doors lock shut beneath them.
GM Execution:
This will be a marathon of rolling, shouting, and resource burning. By making them manually clear every room and every phase of the lift, you aren't just telling them it's hard—you are making them feel the exhaustion of an army of 11,000 machines trying to purge them from the earth.


