PASSIVES
Aerial Dominance: While airborne, cannot be targeted by melee attacks.
Slipstream: Arrows and physical-mass spells (fireballs, ice spikes, standard Destruction/Alteration projectiles) suffer Disadvantage while he's airborne — his speed and displacement make targeting impossible. Exception: Bound Weapons, pure energy spells (raw shock, Sun Fire), and abilities with no physical mass do NOT suffer Disadvantage.
Predator's Focus: Every other round while airborne, Krosulhah uses Blood-Fire Breath targeting the road directly in front of the horses. This is deliberate — he is trying to kill Mable and destroy the cart.

PHASE 1: AIR SUPERIORITY (280 HP — Airborne)
Krosulhah circles above the pass, diving to strafe with Blood-Fire Breath, then pulling up out of melee range. He targets the cart every other round. The party must deal 280 damage to him in the air to ground him.
Brute-forcing 280 HP through DR 12 at Disadvantage will kill the party. They need to use the environment.
THE CART DEFENSE
When Krosulhah targets the horses, the driver must react.
Driver (Bjorn or a player): Hard (-4) Guile (Animal Handling) check.
Success: Bjorn yanks the reins. Mable lurches sideways. The fire scorches the road where they were.
Failure: The horses slip. The cart slams into the cliff wall. The axle shatters. Mable is pinned (3 HP remaining). The cart is dead.
If a player takes the reins from Bjorn, they make the check instead. Bjorn will shout: "Someone grab the reins! I can't — she won't listen to me, she's too scared!"
HOW TO GROUND HIM
THE AVALANCHE (Environmental): The fractured overhang on the eastern cliff. Standard Guile (Perception) to spot it. Deal 60 damage to the rock face (DR 0) to trigger the collapse. If Krosulhah is flying near the eastern wall when it falls: 100 bludgeoning damage. Automatic Stagger for 1 round — uncontested hits while he recovers. This is the single biggest chunk of damage available in Phase 1.
TONAL DISRUPTION (Orion / Kyboh): Use sound or kinetic force against the cliff walls to create a resonant frequency that disrupts his flight. Hard Tonal Engineering check + significant FP spend. Success: Slipstream defense removed for 1 round — all ranged attacks lose Disadvantage.
ICE ARCHITECTURE (Davinia): Build ice pillars or ramps up the cliff face. Melee fighters (Kyboh, Saijah) can climb to a height where they ready an action to strike Krosulhah as he strafes past. Costs FP per structure. The ice holds for 2 rounds before the Shatter-Roar vibration collapses it.
SAIJAH'S AIR DASH: 30ft air dash lets her reach the cliff ledges without climbing. She can position for the avalanche trigger, fire arrows from elevation with Cover, or ready melee strikes as he passes.
ALFONSO'S SHOCK: Raw shock magic has no physical mass — ignores Slipstream. He is the primary ranged damage dealer in Phase 1. His shock spells bypass BOTH the Disadvantage AND the DR 12 (Dwemer Engineering rule carries over — shock ignores DR on constructs, but Krosulhah is not a construct. DR 12 applies to Alfonso's shock against a dragon. He still ignores Slipstream, which is his advantage.)
👁️ DAVINIA SEES: Krosulhah's magical signature is a furnace — raw, ancient, burning. His flight pattern is readable through intent: STRAFE. BURN. CIRCLE. REPEAT. She can predict which direction he's diving from 1 round early, giving the party time to reposition. She can also see the structural weakness in the overhang — the fracture lines glow with stored kinetic energy.
🎵 ORION: Diagnostic Song reveals HP 560, DR 12, the phase bar split, and the Slipstream mechanic. He also hears the resonant frequency of the cliff walls — the data he needs for Tonal Disruption.
GEAR: "Apex aerial predator. DR 12. Phase-divided health architecture. I am recording combat data. Your survival probability is —" pause "— I will keep that figure to myself. It may affect morale."
GEAR's Tonal Pulse does not work on organic creatures. He is support only — Diagnostic Scan to relay information, and panicked narration.

THE CRASH (Phase Transition)
When Phase 1 reaches 0 HP, excess damage is discarded.
"Krosulhah screams — a sound that shakes loose stone from both cliff faces. His left wing buckles, shredded by spell-fire and stone. He rolls in the air, claws scrabbling at nothing, and plummets.
He hits the road like a boulder dropped from the sky. The impact sends a shockwave through the pass — snow and ice and gravel blasting outward in every direction."
All characters: Standard Agility save or knocked Prone and take 15 bludgeoning from flying debris.
Krosulhah is grounded. Wounded. Furious.

PHASE 2: THE DESPERATE STAND (280 HP — Grounded)
The Slipstream is gone. He is melee range. DR 12 is in full effect against standard attacks.
His tactics: Wing Buffet to scatter the party. Bite to execute isolated targets. If the horses/cart are still intact, he crawls toward them to finish the job — the party's tanks must physically body-block a creature that can bite them in half.
Shatter-Roar continues. 2 irreducible to everyone, end of every 2nd player's turn. The attrition never stops.
He fights with cornered fury. No retreat until 60 HP.
THE RETREAT (At 60 HP)
If they cannot kill him:
"Krosulhah snarls, black blood streaming from a dozen wounds. He drags himself toward the cliff face, claws gouging stone. One shattered wing-beat. Two. He hauls himself over the ridge and launches into the grey sky, trailing blood.
The sound of his wing-beats fades. He is gone. But he is not dead."
No soul. No loot. Krosulhah returns in a future session.
THE KILL (At 0 HP)
"Krosulhah crashes onto the frozen road. His massive amber eyes find yours — not with fear, but with a cold, ancient hatred. His jaw opens. A final hiss of superheated air escapes between fangs the length of your forearm.
Then the light goes out of his eyes. The jaw closes. The body settles, steam rising from every wound.
For a moment, nothing. Then the scales begin to glow from within — amber light pushing through the cracks, brighter and brighter, until the body combusts. Not fire. Light. The flesh burns away to nothing. The bones blacken and crack. And from the burning corpse, a torrent of energy erupts — a screaming hurricane of white-gold light, the dragon's soul, ripping free of its broken vessel.
It hangs in the air for one heartbeat. A searing beacon.
Then it moves. Not upward. Not dispersing. It streaks down the road, curving around the bend in the pass toward where Bjorn took the horses. It vanishes behind the cliff wall before you can track it."

GM EYES ONLY: THE SECOND SOUL
Bjorn is around the bend with Mable (alive or dead). He sees the light coming. He has no time to react.
The soul strikes him in the chest. The impact throws him against the cliff wall. For ten seconds his body convulses — bones resetting, muscle rebuilding, decades of age burning away. When it ends, he pushes himself up. The chronic pain in his back is gone. The stiffness in his hands is gone. He has visibly de-aged. His shoulders are broader. His posture is that of a soldier in his prime.
He is terrified. He does not understand what is happening to him. He composes himself before the party arrives.
👁️ DAVINIA SEES (If she's watching the soul's trajectory):
She sees the truth. The streak of light is a vast, ancient consciousness — not dispersing but CHOOSING. It deliberately alters course, drawn to a specific, enormous aura hidden around the bend. She knows where it went. She knows it went to Bjorn.
When she sees Bjorn afterward: his aura has doubled in size. Two dragon souls burning inside a mortal frame. Blinding. Impossible.
CROWN REACTION: Nothing. Ismara says nothing. But Davinia can feel the Crown's attention sharpen. Ismara is VERY interested in what she just witnessed.
THE PHYSICAL PROOF
When the party regroups with Bjorn:
"Bjorn is leaning against the cliff wall, breathing hard. He looks... different. You can't place it at first. Then you realize: he looks younger. Not dramatically — but the deep lines around his eyes have softened. His posture is straighter. His hands, which you've seen stiff and swollen on cold mornings, are steady.
He won't meet your eyes.
'We need to keep moving,' he says. His voice is firmer than you're used to hearing."
If they press him: "I'm fine. Just the adrenaline. Can we go?"
If they press HARDER: "I don't know what happened. I saw the light and then — I don't know. I don't want to talk about it. Please."
He will not confess. He does not understand what he is. But the clues are now impossible to ignore.
LOOT (If killed)
Dragon Bones ×4 (Master-tier crafting)
Dragon Scales ×4 (Master-tier crafting)
Whatever is salvageable from the cart (if destroyed)

AFTERMATH — THE ROAD TO RIFTEN
THE CART
If the cart survived: Damaged but functional. Bjorn drives. The party is battered, low on FP, bleeding. But mobile.
If the cart was destroyed: Mable may be dead or dying. The axle is shattered. They are on foot in a mountain pass with their supplies scattered across frozen ground.
If Mable is dying (3 HP): Danica is not here. Restoration magic can stabilize her. Alfonso's plague magic cannot help a horse. Saijah has no healing. If nobody has Restoration: Mable dies. Bjorn says nothing. He unhitches her body from the wreckage, folds his hands on the cart rail, and stands there for a long time.
If Mable dies, the party walks. They carry what they can. Bjorn carries what he can — and the players may notice he carries MORE than a man his age should be able to. Another clue.
THE JOURNEY
Two days from the pass to Riften. On foot: three.
This is not a montage. It's a march. They are exhausted, wounded, possibly without transport, carrying a dead dragon's bones and a living Dwemer AI. Every camp is cold. Every mile is earned.
The landscape: The foothills flatten into the Rift's golden autumn valleys. The air warms. The trees turn from bare pine to amber and red oak. Familiar territory — they walked this road to Thornheart Grove what feels like a lifetime ago.
Saijah's migraine: It intensifies as they enter the Rift proper. Not the muffled distance of the Pale or the silence of Mzinchaleft. A persistent, grinding pressure behind her left eye. The root network beneath her feet is stressed. Compromised. Not dying — but sick. The Dagon cult's preparatory work is further along here than anywhere she's felt.
GEAR on the surface world: He is experiencing everything for the first time. Trees. Wind. Rain. Animals. He narrates constantly unless told to stop.
"That organism is converting sunlight into chemical energy through its epidermis. Remarkable. It has been doing this for approximately forty years based on its trunk diameter. I have been operational for 4,287 years and have never performed photosynthesis. I feel this is a gap in my dataset."
"The quadruped pulling your conveyance appears distressed. Is this standard operational behaviour for biological transport units?" (About Mable, if alive.)
"Your ambient body temperature has dropped 0.4 degrees since sunset. Is this a concern, or do you simply accept gradual thermal death as a feature of organic existence?"
He is genuinely delighted to be outside. He is also completely insufferable about it.
Bjorn: Quieter each day. Stronger each day. If he lifts something heavy, he catches himself and looks at his own hands like they belong to someone else. If he's driving the cart, the horses respond to him differently — calmer, more obedient. Animals can sense what he's becoming even if he can't.

THE GATES OF RIFTEN
THE FIRST SIGHT
"You crest the last hill before the Rift valley opens below you. And there it is — Riften, sitting on the shore of Lake Honrich exactly where you left it. The autumn canopy frames the city walls in gold and amber and red. Smoke rises from chimneys, not pyres. The lake shimmers in the afternoon light.
No black flags. No barricades. No locked gates. No army of the desperate and dying pressed against the walls begging for entry.
The road ahead is clear. A merchant cart is rolling toward the city from the south. Two fishermen are walking home with their catch. A child is throwing stones into the lake.
The city you traveled for days to save does not need saving. It barely looks like it noticed anything happened."
Let the table sit with this. Do not narrate past it. Let them arrive at the gates in their own time.
THE GATE
A guard glances at the cart — or at the battered, exhausted group on foot — and waves them through.
"Welcome back to Riften."
If they ask the guard about the plague: "Sorted. Your priestess handled it — the Lantern one. Black-Briar's paying for the cleanup. You lot are popular around here."
"Your priestess." He knows they're Lanterns. He's crediting THEIR company. For something they had nothing to do with.
THE NOTICE
Posted at the gate on official parchment with Maven Black-Briar's seal:
"The people of the Rift owe their lives to the courage and devotion of the OBSIDIAN LANTERNS and their priestess DANICA PURE-SPRING. Through her tireless efforts and personal sacrifice, the contagion that threatened our city has been eradicated and our beloved Hemming Black-Briar restored to health. The Black-Briar family extends its eternal gratitude."
The Obsidian Lanterns are on the wall. Their name. Their company. For something none of them did. The greatest heroic act the Lanterns have ever performed happened entirely because the party was not there.

End of session.

SESSION GM NOTES
The breathing room is sacred. After Mzinchaleft and before the dragon, the players need space. Do not fill it. If they want to talk, facilitate. If they want silence, give them landscape descriptions and let GEAR be weird about trees.
The dragon fight is a resource check. The party just escaped a dungeon. Their FP may be low. Their HP may be low. Krosulhah does not care. He is not calibrated to their current state — he is calibrated to kill them. The escape's cost directly impacts the dragon fight's difficulty.
Bjorn's transformation is visible. Do not hide it. The de-aging, the strength, the horses responding differently — these are observable facts. Whether the party investigates or lets it slide is their choice. Davinia, if she was watching, KNOWS. What she does with that knowledge is her arc.
Riften is the gut punch. The Lanterns' name is on that notice. Their company saved a city, cured a plague, rescued Maven's heir. And none of them were in the room when it happened. The only truly heroic thing the Obsidian Lanterns have done since becoming the Lanterns happened because the party was somewhere else entirely. That should sting worse than being forgotten.
GEAR at the gates of Riften is seeing a city for the first time. He has never seen organic architecture, commerce, social hierarchy, or children. He will have questions. Many questions. Save them for next session.

